  <title>Deconstructing “Just and Proper”: Arguments in Favor of Adopting the “Remedial Purpose” Approach to Section 10(j) Labor Injunctions</title>
  <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.michiganlawreview.org/articles/deconstructing-just-and-proper-arguments-in-favor-of-adopting-the-remedial-purpose-approach-to-section-10-j-labor-injunctions"></link>
  <updated>2011-09-27T18:22:35Z</updated>
  <author>
    <name>admin</name>
  </author>
  <id>630</id>
  <summary type="text">Congress, through the 1947 addition of section 10(j) to the National 
Labor Relations Act, authoriz[...]</summary>
  <content type="text/html"><![CDATA[<p>Congress, through the 1947 addition of section 10(j) to the National 
Labor Relations Act, authorized district courts to grant preliminary 
injunctive relief for unfair labor practices if they deem such relief 
&ldquo;just and proper.&rdquo; To this day a circuit split persists over the correct
 interpretation of this &ldquo;just and proper&rdquo; standard. Some circuits 
interpret &ldquo;just and proper&rdquo; to require application of the traditional 
equitable principles approach that normally governs preliminary 
injunctions. Other circuits interpret &ldquo;just and proper&rdquo; to require an 
analysis of whether injunctive relief is necessary to preserve the 
National Labor Relations Board&rsquo;s remedial power. This Note examines the 
justifications behind these two interpretations in light of section 
10(j)&rsquo;s statutory structure&mdash;most notably, the use of the just and proper 
standard in two other provisions of the National Labor Relations Act. It
 also considers the legislative history of section 10(j) and the public policy 
consequences underlying Congress&rsquo;s mandate granting the Board exclusive 
jurisdiction to seek injunctive relief in court under section 10(j). 
This Note argues that an examination of these factors reveals that 
Congress intended for courts to focus their section 10(j) analysis on 
the preservation of the National Labor Relations Board&rsquo;s remedial power 
rather than on traditional equitable principles.</p>]]></content>
