<entry>
  <title>Using Public Disclosure as the Vesting Point for Moral Rights Under the Visual Artists Rights Act  </title>
  <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.michiganlawreview.org/articles/using-public-disclosure-as-the-vesting-point-for-moral-rights-under-the-visual-artists-rights-act"></link>
  <updated>2011-09-27T18:18:40Z</updated>
  <author>
    <name>admin</name>
  </author>
  <id>629</id>
  <summary type="text">In 2010, the Court of Appeals for the First Circuit confronted the 
novel question of when moral ri[...]</summary>
  <content type="text/html"><![CDATA[<p>In 2010, the Court of Appeals for the First Circuit confronted the 
novel question of when moral rights protections vest under the Visual 
Artists Rights Act. In <em>Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art Foundation, Inc. v. B&uuml;chel</em>, the First Circuit determined that the protections of the Visual Artists Rights Act begin when a work is &ldquo;created&rdquo; under the Copyright Act. This Note argues that this decision harms moral rights conceptually and is likely to result in unpredictable and inconsistent decisions. This Note proposes instead that these statutory protections should vest when an artist determines that his work is complete and presents it to the public. This standard is more consistent with the history of moral rights. Additionally, public access is necessary to justify a treatment of art different from that of other types of property, and it is a more essential component of moral rights than an artist&rsquo;s feelings of connection to his work. Finally, the legislative intent behind the Visual Artists Rights Act and the reasoning in previous judicial decisions are more accurately reflected by a public 
disclosure standard. Utilizing &ldquo;creation&rdquo; as a vesting point for moral 
rights is not supported by the history of the Visual Artists Rights Act and will result in uncertainty and inconsistency in future decisions.</p>]]></content>
</entry>
<entry>
  <title>Stare Decisis and Constitutional Text</title>
  <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.michiganlawreview.org/articles/stare-decisis-and-constitutional-text"></link>
  <updated>2011-09-27T18:12:26Z</updated>
  <author>
    <name>admin</name>
  </author>
  <id>628</id>
  <summary type="text">Almost everyone acknowledges that stare decisis should play a 
significant role when the Supreme Co[...]</summary>
  <content type="text/html"><![CDATA[<p>Almost everyone acknowledges that stare decisis should play a 
significant role when the Supreme Court of the United States resolves 
constitutional cases. Yet the academic and judicial rationales for this 
practice tend to rely on naked consequentialist considerations, and make
 only passing efforts to square the Court&rsquo;s stare decisis doctrines with
 the language of the Constitution. This Article offers a qualified 
defense of constitutional stare decisis that rests exclusively on 
constitutional text. It aims to broaden the overlapping consensus of 
interpretive theories that can support a role for constitutional stare 
decisis, but to do this it must narrow the circumstances in which stare decisis can be applied.</p>]]></content>
</entry>
<entry>
  <title>Rethinking Discrimination Law</title>
  <link rel="alternate" href="http://www.michiganlawreview.org/articles/rethinking-discrimination-law"></link>
  <updated>2011-09-27T18:06:41Z</updated>
  <author>
    <name>admin</name>
  </author>
  <id>627</id>
  <summary type="text">Modern employment discrimination law is defined by an increasingly 
complex set of frameworks. Thes[...]</summary>
  <content type="text/html"><![CDATA[<p>Modern employment discrimination law is defined by an increasingly 
complex set of frameworks. These frameworks structure the ways that 
courts, juries, and litigants think about discrimination. This Article 
challenges whether courts should use the frameworks to conceptualize 
discrimination. It argues that just as faulty sorting contributes to 
stereotyping and societal discrimination, courts are using faulty 
structures to substantively limit discrimination claims.<br />This Article
 makes three central contributions. First, it demonstrates how 
discrimination analysis has been reduced to a rote sorting process. It recognizes and makes explicit courts' methodology so that the structure 
of discrimination analysis and its effects can be examined. Second, it demonstrates how the frameworks tend to squeeze out claims that are 
arguably cognizable under the federal discrimination statutes' broad 
operative language. This Article's final contribution is to propose a 
simpler model for thinking about employment discrimination law. It 
argues for a return to first principles that would require courts to 
specifically define key statutory language.</p>]]></content>
